      <!-- Prescription vs. Supplement -->
      <h2>Prescription Treatments vs. Hair Growth Gummies</h2>

      <p>It is important to understand where supplements fit within the broader landscape of hair loss treatment. The FDA has approved two medications for hair loss: <strong>minoxidil</strong> (Rogaine), a topical vasodilator that stimulates follicle blood flow, and <strong>finasteride</strong> (Propecia), an oral 5-alpha-reductase inhibitor that blocks DHT production. Both have extensive clinical evidence supporting their efficacy for androgenetic alopecia.</p>

      <div class="tip-box"><div class="tip-box-ico">i</div><p><strong>Gummies complement, not replace.</strong> Hair growth gummies address nutritional deficiencies that exacerbate thinning, support existing hair health, and may slow early-stage thinning through natural DHT inhibition (saw palmetto). Many dermatologists recommend a combined approach: prescription treatment for the hormonal component and supplementation for the nutritional component.</p></div>

      <div class="warn-box"><div class="warn-box-ico">!</div><p>If your hair loss is <strong>sudden, patchy, or accompanied by other symptoms</strong> (fatigue, weight changes, scalp irritation), consult a dermatologist before starting any supplement. These patterns may indicate thyroid disorders, alopecia areata, or iron-deficiency anemia that require medical treatment.</p></div>

